11:14.132 --> 11:16.259
This is not a science,
it's an art.

11:16.259 --> 11:18.720
<i>So sometimes, you just have</i>
<i>to go with what's happening,</i>

11:18.720 --> 11:20.346
and this is what's happening.

11:20.346 --> 11:23.808
80% of it is done,
so we're looking good.

11:23.808 --> 11:26.436
If the welds are good,
even a light blade,

11:26.436 --> 11:28.354
it should survive
the antler chop.

11:28.354 --> 11:30.440
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

11:30.440 --> 11:33.109
- Bladesmiths, 45 minutes.

11:33.109 --> 11:36.237
You have only 45 minutes
remaining to finish your work.

11:36.237 --> 11:37.530
- Ah!

11:37.530 --> 11:39.532
- Devin's doing an amazing job.

11:39.532 --> 11:40.867
That looks like
a good weld to me, J.

11:40.867 --> 11:42.911
- It does.

11:42.911 --> 11:45.955
<i>- I'm happy with my weld,</i>
<i>but I look at the sides,</i>

11:45.955 --> 11:49.042
and I can see that the rebar
has separated a little bit.

11:49.042 --> 11:50.960
<i>But to me, it looks like</i>
<i>the Grand Canyon.</i>

11:50.960 --> 11:52.378
It's not gonna break.

11:52.378 --> 11:55.340
Ugly, but it's
gonna do its job.

11:55.340 --> 11:57.175
- And here comes Gordy's hammer
flying through the air.

11:57.175 --> 11:58.551
- You got it, buddy.

11:58.551 --> 12:00.220
- This is working,
but it's hot.

12:00.220 --> 12:02.597
But you see, it's only
the outside that's hot.

12:02.597 --> 12:04.182
The inside core is not
glowing red at all.

12:04.182 --> 12:05.516
- It's not gonna weld.

12:05.516 --> 12:07.227
It's not going
to weld that way.

12:07.227 --> 12:08.853
<i>- I'm hammering and hammering,</i>

12:08.853 --> 12:10.605
<i>but my welds</i>
<i>are just not sticking.</i>

12:10.605 --> 12:12.148
- Is that a heat problem, J?

12:12.148 --> 12:14.442
- Overheating,
and having dirty steel.

12:14.442 --> 12:17.070
That bar is just not
gonna stick together.

12:17.070 --> 12:19.072
<i>- I'm having issues</i>
<i>with the heating.</i>

12:19.072 --> 12:20.990
It's just problem
after problem.

12:20.990 --> 12:22.700
<i>I got to figure out something,</i>

12:22.700 --> 12:24.327
<i>because I'm wasting</i>
<i>a lot of time here</i>

12:24.327 --> 12:25.453
<i>just pounding away on this.</i>

12:25.453 --> 12:27.664
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

12:27.664 --> 12:29.332
I ain't
going nowhere with this.

12:29.332 --> 12:30.750
I'm going
to have to start over.

12:30.750 --> 12:33.670
- Oh, no.

12:33.670 --> 12:35.171
- Oh, no.
Gordy's starting over again.

12:35.171 --> 12:37.507
- Oh, my God.

12:37.507 --> 12:40.885
- But what Gordy needs to do
is get flat, even pieces.

12:40.885 --> 12:42.845
Then it'll take easier.

12:42.845 --> 12:46.516
- I run over, I get more
of the fire ring pit.

12:46.516 --> 12:49.560
<i>I realize that I've only got</i>
<i>one type of steel.</i>

12:49.560 --> 12:53.106
So then I resorted back
to another tent stake.

12:53.106 --> 12:56.109
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

12:56.109 --> 12:57.485
I'm trying.

12:57.485 --> 12:59.195
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

12:59.195 --> 13:01.447
- When Trevor hits that metal,
listen to it.

13:01.447 --> 13:03.533
it sounds like
"kuh-lack, kuh-lack, kuh-lack"

13:03.533 --> 13:04.784
as opposed to
"ding, ding, ding."

13:04.784 --> 13:06.452
It's not--it's not forgeable.

13:06.452 --> 13:07.954
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:07.954 --> 13:09.622
- [bleep].

13:09.622 --> 13:12.000
<i>If I have a bad weld</i>
<i>on this knife,</i>

13:12.000 --> 13:14.877
basically, when he goes
to chop into this antler,

13:14.877 --> 13:16.337
those sides
are going to pop off,

13:16.337 --> 13:17.880
and there's
going to be a failure.

13:17.880 --> 13:19.966
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:19.966 --> 13:22.844
<i>My best bet is definitely</i>
<i>going to be a edge quench.</i>

13:22.844 --> 13:25.930
<i>That way,</i>
<i>I have a limited risk</i>

13:25.930 --> 13:30.143
of my San Mai blowing open,
and I still get a hard edge.

13:30.143 --> 13:33.062
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

13:33.062 --> 13:38.401
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:38.401 --> 13:40.153
- That wasn't in the oil
very long.

13:40.153 --> 13:42.822
- Really, you still alive?

13:42.822 --> 13:46.409
Yay, I got a straight blade.
All right.

13:46.409 --> 13:49.871
But it's a soft edge, so I have
to quench this thing again.

13:49.871 --> 13:53.875
- Bladesmiths, five minutes.
Five minutes remaining.

13:53.875 --> 13:56.127
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

13:56.127 --> 13:58.713
- Get that ready for
the heat treat, it's coming up.

13:58.713 --> 14:02.592
- Devin is really getting
his fire cranked up now.

14:02.592 --> 14:04.218
He's forged
that blade to shape.

14:04.218 --> 14:06.179
He's got
a thinner edge than spine.

14:06.179 --> 14:08.056
Could he burn this steel up?
- Oh, yeah.

14:08.056 --> 14:10.558
- Here we go.

14:10.558 --> 14:11.851
- Devin didn't even
look at the temperature.

14:11.851 --> 14:13.436
- I think he was trying.

14:13.436 --> 14:14.896
It looked red
in the core of the blade.

14:14.896 --> 14:16.230
- It did,
I wasn't sure if it was

14:16.230 --> 14:17.523
all the way through, though.

14:17.523 --> 14:21.694
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:21.694 --> 14:24.489
- Mike also quenched
right next to Devin.

14:24.489 --> 14:26.616
<i>[tense music]</i>

14:26.616 --> 14:28.242
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:28.242 --> 14:29.619
- Well, we'll see.

14:29.619 --> 14:32.538
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

14:32.538 --> 14:34.707
- The blade came out straight,
so it's good.

14:34.707 --> 14:36.084
I'm gonna go with that.

14:36.084 --> 14:38.586
But the devil
is in the details.

14:38.586 --> 14:42.799
So I'm gonna clean up
the blade as best I can.

14:42.799 --> 14:44.759
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:44.759 --> 14:47.136
- Gordy's swinging
that huge hammer.

14:47.136 --> 14:48.513
- It's getting the heat out,

14:48.513 --> 14:50.306
but that's still
a single piece of steel.

14:50.306 --> 14:53.142
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:53.142 --> 14:55.520
- It's not looking good.
- It's not looking good.

14:55.520 --> 14:58.523
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

14:58.523 --> 15:01.651
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:03.027 --> 15:05.238
- Trevor went in
for a second quench just now.

15:05.238 --> 15:08.116
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:08.116 --> 15:09.992
- Oh, oh, popped welds.

15:09.992 --> 15:12.662
You can see them on the side
of Trevor's blade.

15:12.662 --> 15:15.790
One of those welds has
popped out and warped away.

15:15.790 --> 15:17.917
<i>- These delams are--</i>
<i>There a big deal.</i>

15:17.917 --> 15:20.294
<i>I mean, this could</i>
<i>definitely send me home.</i>

15:20.294 --> 15:23.297
If I had more time,
I would try to forge weld

15:23.297 --> 15:26.050
these delaminations shut,
but I don't.

15:26.050 --> 15:27.718
<i>I'm out of time.</i>

15:27.718 --> 15:29.554
I'm gonna polish a turd.

15:29.554 --> 15:32.515
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

15:32.515 --> 15:34.475
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:34.475 --> 15:39.730
- Ten, nine, eight, seven, six,

15:39.730 --> 15:44.819
five, four, three, two, one.

15:44.819 --> 15:47.655
Bladesmiths,
this round is over.

15:47.655 --> 15:49.991
<i>[tense music]</i>

15:49.991 --> 15:51.701
- Holy cow.

15:51.701 --> 15:54.036
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:54.036 --> 15:56.164
<i>- I'm kicking myself.</i>

15:56.164 --> 15:57.790
<i>I put in the effort.</i>

15:57.790 --> 16:00.543
I put in all the power
I possibly could.

16:00.543 --> 16:03.296
<i>But I don't have</i>
<i>a San Mai piece.</i>

16:03.296 --> 16:06.299
<i>[dramatic musical flourish]</i>

16:06.299 --> 16:09.427
- Bladesmiths, that was a tough
first round of competition.

16:09.427 --> 16:11.554
However, at the end
of this round,

16:11.554 --> 16:14.140
you were to have
a signature San Mai blade

16:14.140 --> 16:15.474
quenched and hardened.

16:15.474 --> 16:18.060
Gordy, your blade
is not quenched,

16:18.060 --> 16:20.271
it's not hardened,
it's not a San Mai.

16:20.271 --> 16:22.940
You failed
to meet the parameters.

16:22.940 --> 16:25.568
However, it's about heart.

16:25.568 --> 16:29.322
And you went out like any
champion should: Swinging.

16:29.322 --> 16:31.866
And we appreciate that.
- Thank you.

16:31.866 --> 16:35.578
- But Gordy, I have to ask you
to please leave camp.

16:35.578 --> 16:36.746
- Heard.

16:36.746 --> 16:39.540
<i>[tense music]</i>

16:39.540 --> 16:41.959
<i>I didn't turn in</i>
<i>anything close</i>

16:41.959 --> 16:44.337
<i>to what their parameters were.</i>

16:44.337 --> 16:47.590
I worked my butt off.
Um, I did my best.

16:47.590 --> 16:50.760
<i>It was overwhelming for me,</i>
<i>but I wasn't gonna give up,</i>

16:50.760 --> 16:52.762
<i>because that's not</i>
<i>the person that I am.</i>

16:52.762 --> 16:54.639
I am upset with myself.

16:54.639 --> 16:57.266
But I'm gonna
keep making blades,

16:57.266 --> 17:00.186
<i>and I'm going home</i>
<i>with my head held high.</i>

17:00.186 --> 17:03.522
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:03.522 --> 17:05.107
- Bladesmiths,
welcome back from camp

17:05.107 --> 17:07.193
and welcome to The Forge.

17:07.193 --> 17:10.154
That was tough enough to cause
a round one parameter failure.

17:10.154 --> 17:12.698
That doesn't mean that you're
safe from elimination.

17:12.698 --> 17:15.284
So it's time for
the judges' critique.

17:15.284 --> 17:16.744
Trevor, you're up first.

17:16.744 --> 17:18.454
Please present your blade
to the judges.

17:18.454 --> 17:20.873
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

17:20.873 --> 17:22.458
<i>- This is probably</i>
<i>one of the widest blades</i>

17:22.458 --> 17:24.293
<i>we've ever had turned in</i>
<i>in round one.</i>

17:24.293 --> 17:26.295
It feels like
it's a real chopper.

17:26.295 --> 17:27.964
The main concern
with your San Mai

17:27.964 --> 17:29.674
is you've got
some metal flaps coming apart,

17:29.674 --> 17:31.759
<i>especially on the spine.</i>

17:31.759 --> 17:33.427
If I were you,
I'd definitely address this,

17:33.427 --> 17:35.346
because I will never
pick up a blade

17:35.346 --> 17:37.265
that has cracks
and openings in it.

17:37.265 --> 17:39.934
But I like your design.
- Thank you.

17:39.934 --> 17:41.435
- All right, Mike.

17:41.435 --> 17:43.145
Please present
your blade to the judges.

17:43.145 --> 17:45.940
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

17:45.940 --> 17:47.858
<i>- Mike, you've got</i>
<i>some issues here.</i>

17:47.858 --> 17:50.820
You've got a wave
going down your blade.

17:50.820 --> 17:54.073
You've got delaminations
all the way around.

17:54.073 --> 17:56.200
And I can see the light
through the tip here.

17:56.200 --> 17:57.827
<i>It's almost</i>
<i>like a snake tongue.</i>

17:57.827 --> 17:59.745
And it's also
a very lean piece.

17:59.745 --> 18:01.789
Maybe try to close them up

18:01.789 --> 18:05.001
and add some more mass to this,
especially in your tang.

18:05.001 --> 18:06.502
- All right, Devin.

18:06.502 --> 18:08.337
Please present
your blade to the judges.

18:08.337 --> 18:10.798
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

18:10.798 --> 18:12.341
<i>- There's a lot of steel here.</i>

18:12.341 --> 18:14.343
<i>It was really impressive</i>
<i>to watch you</i>

18:14.343 --> 18:16.470
forge weld this together.
- Thank you.

18:16.470 --> 18:18.055
- There are still
some visible delams,

18:18.055 --> 18:20.182
<i>but it's still solid.</i>

18:20.182 --> 18:21.767
And it would be nice to see

18:21.767 --> 18:24.145
some kind of a stop
at the back of this.

18:24.145 --> 18:27.106
This is kind of
asking to go flying.

18:27.106 --> 18:30.276
But um, really well done.
Impressive to watch.

18:30.276 --> 18:31.611
- Thank you.

18:31.611 --> 18:33.821
- All right, Bladesmiths.

18:33.821 --> 18:35.489
The judges have agreed, you're
all moving into round two.

18:35.489 --> 18:37.158
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

18:37.158 --> 18:38.951
- Now that your blades
have been tempered,

18:38.951 --> 18:40.745
it's time to turn them
into fully functional weapons

18:40.745 --> 18:42.455
by attaching handles to them.

18:42.455 --> 18:46.042
However, you can only use
bone, horn, or antler

18:46.042 --> 18:47.752
for your handle scales.

18:47.752 --> 18:50.254
You will have three hours
in this round.

18:50.254 --> 18:52.173
You can use some of that time
to address the flaws

18:52.173 --> 18:53.507
that were identified
in your blades,

18:53.507 --> 18:55.051
and I highly suggest
that you do.

18:55.051 --> 18:56.927
Because at the end
of this round,

18:56.927 --> 18:59.263
your weapons will be tested
for strength and durability

18:59.263 --> 19:01.265
in an antler chop,
and for edge retention

19:01.265 --> 19:02.475
in that ham slice.

19:02.475 --> 19:04.060
<i>[dramatic musical flourish]</i>

19:04.060 --> 19:06.437
Good luck, gents.
Your three hours starts now.

19:06.437 --> 19:08.147
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

19:08.147 --> 19:10.316
- And off they go.
- Off to the races.

19:10.316 --> 19:12.485
- Devin's going straight
to the welder.

19:12.485 --> 19:14.278
<i>- I know the first thing</i>
<i>I need to do</i>

19:14.278 --> 19:16.989
is fill in
the Grand Canyon on my blade.

19:16.989 --> 19:19.575
- Getting that weld
all the way into that seam.

19:19.575 --> 19:22.953
I'd start grinding it first,
and then weld it.

19:22.953 --> 19:25.122
- My big concern
is to try to maintain

19:25.122 --> 19:28.167
my heat treat and temper as is.

19:28.167 --> 19:30.419
Weld the other side.

19:30.419 --> 19:32.171
<i>I'm not the best welder.</i>

19:32.171 --> 19:34.590
<i>So I'm gonna do</i>
<i>the best job that I can</i>

19:34.590 --> 19:36.008
<i>and see where I end up.</i>

19:36.008 --> 19:37.968
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

19:37.968 --> 19:41.889
- The worst thing you could do
is not finish your blade.

19:41.889 --> 19:44.058
<i>My game plan</i>
<i>is to work on the handle.</i>

19:44.058 --> 19:46.143
<i>Get that out of the way.</i>

19:46.143 --> 19:48.437
<i>I'm going to be putting</i>
<i>a nice, large</i>

19:48.437 --> 19:50.856
<i>moose horn handle on it.</i>

19:50.856 --> 19:53.401
<i>There's really</i>
<i>only one downside</i>

19:53.401 --> 19:55.820
of working
with antler material

19:55.820 --> 19:57.863
is it stinks like hell

19:57.863 --> 20:00.616
when you have to
use a power tool on it.

20:00.616 --> 20:02.618
- That's not healthy.

20:02.618 --> 20:04.412
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

20:04.412 --> 20:06.706
<i>- So the judges pointed out</i>
<i>my cold shuts,</i>

20:06.706 --> 20:08.290
<i>and it is</i>
<i>a big concern for me.</i>

20:08.290 --> 20:10.251
<i>It's a weak point.</i>

20:10.251 --> 20:13.045
So what I'm going to try to do
is some exploratory surgery

20:13.045 --> 20:14.755
<i>and see where</i>
<i>those cold shuts really are</i>

20:14.755 --> 20:16.549
<i>and how deep they go.</i>

20:16.549 --> 20:17.925
- I got a feeling he's
going to keep grinding that,

20:17.925 --> 20:19.635
try and make it thinner,

20:19.635 --> 20:21.262
and then those voids
are going to pop back up,

20:21.262 --> 20:23.305
because the bead
didn't go all the way down.

20:23.305 --> 20:25.266
<i>- As I'm grinding this blade,</i>

20:25.266 --> 20:27.184
<i>I'm seeing that those</i>
<i>cold shuts are pretty bad.</i>

20:29.520 --> 20:31.856
<i>I have to be careful because</i>
<i>my blade's already thin.</i>

20:31.856 --> 20:33.441
<i>And if I grind away</i>
<i>too much material,</i>

20:33.441 --> 20:35.234
<i>I just create another problem.</i>

20:35.234 --> 20:37.695
<i>So my only option</i>
<i>is to go to the welder.</i>

20:37.695 --> 20:40.781
<i>I'm trying to tack it</i>
<i>right in the seam.</i>

20:40.781 --> 20:43.033
<i>Hopefully,</i>
<i>it holds it in place.</i>

20:43.033 --> 20:44.869
- One hour has elapsed.

20:44.869 --> 20:48.289
You have two hours remaining
to finish your blades.

20:48.289 --> 20:51.000
<i>- So I get the crack in my</i>
<i>blade filled with the welder.</i>

20:51.000 --> 20:53.210
<i>Go to the pantry</i>
<i>to look for a piece</i>

20:53.210 --> 20:55.337
<i>of proper antler material.</i>

20:55.337 --> 20:58.424
It's more difficult
to find the perfect piece

20:58.424 --> 21:01.010
of organic material
formed in nature

21:01.010 --> 21:04.889
<i>to fit a curved tang</i>
<i>on my big, heavy blade.</i>

21:04.889 --> 21:07.850
Usually,
I find the antler first,

21:07.850 --> 21:10.561
and make the knife
to fit the antler.

21:10.561 --> 21:13.731
I find a very nice piece
of water buffalo horn.

21:13.731 --> 21:16.192
<i>I can make</i>
<i>a multi-piece handle</i>

21:16.192 --> 21:17.943
<i>to fit the curve of my tang.</i>

21:17.943 --> 21:19.361
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

21:19.361 --> 21:21.614
<i>- When you're mixing epoxy,</i>

21:21.614 --> 21:25.284
<i>if you mix a bit of iron</i>
<i>filings or sawdust in with it,</i>

21:25.284 --> 21:27.661
it gives it
quite a bit more grip.

21:27.661 --> 21:30.790
- Mike has a lot of issues
to work on with his blade.

21:30.790 --> 21:32.458
And most of the things
he could have done

21:32.458 --> 21:34.251
to fix it involve heat.

21:34.251 --> 21:37.755
And he's got his handle
epoxyed on already.

21:37.755 --> 21:40.049
If he puts a bunch of heat
into that blade,

21:40.049 --> 21:42.384
he's going to lose
the structural integrity

21:42.384 --> 21:44.178
of the epoxy that's holding
that handle together.

21:44.178 --> 21:45.387
<i>[heavy rock music]</i>

21:45.387 --> 21:46.931
<i>- I've got the blade welded</i>

21:46.931 --> 21:48.766
<i>and kind of</i>
<i>cleaned up a little bit.</i>

21:48.766 --> 21:50.142
And it still
looks like something

21:50.142 --> 21:51.936
out of a zombie movie.

21:51.936 --> 21:55.439
<i>Next, I have to choose</i>
<i>my handle material.</i>

21:55.439 --> 21:58.359
<i>I'm looking at the bones,</i>
<i>the antlers and the horns,</i>

21:58.359 --> 22:00.945
<i>and I see this</i>
<i>one piece of antler.</i>

22:00.945 --> 22:03.989
It's crooked,
but it feels good.

22:03.989 --> 22:05.324
<i>So I'm like,</i>
<i>I think I can work with this.</i>

22:05.324 --> 22:07.368
<i>I can do something with this.</i>

22:09.620 --> 22:10.913
- Trevor knows the teeth
are on the other side

22:10.913 --> 22:12.289
of that saw, right?

22:12.289 --> 22:13.874
- He's going to be there
a long time

22:13.874 --> 22:15.668
when he's on
the wrong side of a band saw.

22:15.668 --> 22:17.002
- Whoops!

22:17.002 --> 22:17.962
